                           </table><center>  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - WIZARD</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>1-20 AS A HIGH ELF WIZARD FOR XP AND MONEY</font> - <small>Kytharia Shadowsprite, The Rathe</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>High elf wizards are one of the great class combinations in EQ. Noble and proud, they fight for the good of Norrath. Plus, high elven chicks look cute in robes.

There are tons of guides out there to help you pass your early years, but I tried to make this one a little different, because I like to explore and there are some places I can’t stand going. Rest assured I know where to get great xp and money =)

Starting out in Felwithe, you’ll want to learn your spells and go just outside the gates, fighting mainly bats and decaying skeletons. You could also fight wasps, but as bat wings sell to other players for 2pp per stack and bone chips can go for as much as 5pp per stack depending on the need, we’ll stick with these for now.

When you ding 2, which shouldn’t take long, head back inside Felwithe and train some skills, and sell off anything other than batwings or bone chips. By now you might have enough money to buy another spell or two, if so I recommend Shock of Frost and True North. The thing about wizard spells is, most of them are pretty useless. At level 13, I had 21 spells, so don’t worry if you miss a couple.

Also pick up a letter from Taccar Tissleplay while in Felwithe, and exit, going off down the road. Take the first branch to the right, which is just a short ways from the gate, and you’ll eventually reach the wood elf city of Kelethin, which has a much better newbie area than Kelethin, and often has higher levels offering free buffs. Accept them gratefully if you get a chance.

Now you’ll want to go up the first lift and go across the bridge to the right. Now there should be another bridge to the left, with a building called Songweavers’ Guild. Go in there and give the letter you picked up to Jakum Webdancer. You’ll get good xp and between 1 and 6 gp. Now backtrack back to the lift and head back down, and go straight out from the lift. Here you’ll want to fight more bats and skellies, as well as pixie tricksters and orcs pawns. Watch out when fighting pixies, though, as they will gang up on you and guards won’t help you. If you get in trouble, run around typing /y, or, even better, make a hotkey for it. Sell any weapons you get, and soon you’ll have enough money for a backpack or two.

Now, continue like this, adding widow hatchlings at 3, until you hit level 4. Any pieces of cloth armor that drop from the creatures, you’ll want to equip. You should also equip a cracked staff when you can. They drop pretty often from decaying skellies, and blunt weapons will be better for you for now, anyway.

Now it’s time to head back to Felwithe and train some more skills and buy your new spells. If you kept all your bat wings and bone chips and sold them to players, you should easily have enough money for all your spells, and maybe even a senior apprentice robe. If not, I’d recommend buying Shock of Fire, Root, Gate, & Fade, in that order. You’ll want to make sure to put at least 1 point into Meditate, which will speed up your mana regen a lot.

Now we’re going to do something a little different. If you’re anything like me, you’re probably sick of Gfay by now. So, get someone to show you to Butcherblock, and keep going until you reach a crossroad with a guardhouse. This is a great place to hunt, if you get in trouble just run to the guards. For now you’ll want to look for skunks, and maybe large snakes, but be sure to /con them first. You should hit 5 in no time, then you might be able to mix in the occasional wandering goblin depending on its con. This can be done solo, but you can be much more adventurous with a partner, preferably a warrior, ranger, bard, or paladin.

If you happen to get 4 Skunk Scent Glands or 4 Runnyeye Warbeads, you can run to the dwarf city of Kaladim, which is down the right fork from the crossroad. The warbeads can be given to Byzar Bloodforge in the dwarf warriors’ guild, and the glands can be given to the dwarf in the back left of the cleric guild, I forget his name.

Anyway, now you’re level 6, and most people would go back to Gfay and head to Orc Hill, maybe even Crushbone. Well, I hate Orc Hill, and I hate Crushbone. On Orc Hill there are too many orcs unless you have a full group, and inside CB there are those wonderful trains where you get killed in 1.3 seconds. So you can stay in Kaladim, with a partner, and kill more snakes, goblins, and giant bats, or you can go to Steamfont to hunt in a small group at the windmills. I prefer Steamfont. Zone back into Gfay and send a shout, someone will usually show you the way.

Fighting at the windmills is fun, and you should easily be able to hit level 8. Now head (or gate) back to Felwithe to buy your level 8 spells. The most important of these are Shock of Ice, Lesser Shielding, and Shadow Step. The rest can wait if necessary, and in fact aren’t really that important anyway.

Now’s when the fun starts. You’ll want to try to get a port to West Commons. If you can’t, then head back to BB and make the long run to the docks and take the even longer boat ride to Freeport. If you do get a port, be sure to get a sow, and run eastward, through East Commons and into Freeport. You’ll want to get a bind here, I didn’t, and believe me, it’s not fun to die and come back in front of Felwithe.

Once you’re bound in Freeport, run back to East Commons and shout that you’re looking to join an orc group. If you can get in a group, get someone to show you to the camp, and you can easily get good xp up to 10, 11 if you squeeze it. You’ll also come across Deathfist Slashed Belts, which you can turn in in Freeport on the roof of the Militia house for good xp and a bit of gold, or you can sell for between 1-5pp to other players, usually 2 or 3. I’d personally recommend turning them in until level 10, and if you continue to fight orcs, sell them to other players at 10.

Now at 10, or still at 8 if you couldn’t find an orc group, you’ll want to head to the Tunnel in EC, which is the zone to North Ro. Here you’ll want to have at least Root, Lesser Shielding, Shock of Ice, Shadow Step, and Gate learned. Sit and med to full, and then go out in front of the tunnel and you’ll learn what it means to root and nuke.

Whenever you find something that /cons blue to you, or maybe black, but not asps just yet, root it, then start nuking it. If it breaks root, reroot it and start again. The great place about the Tunnel is that there are always high levels sitting around just buying and selling who will often help you if you’re in trouble. Don’t be afraid to yell.

If you started this at 10, you can go ahead and take blue asps, but watch out for their poison. It’s nasty, and all the more reason to root them and stay away. At 11, it’s a good idea to leave these behind. The next level you might want to get a partner, a tank class is good, but you can do it solo. You’ll want to fight Wisps, the little blue glowing dots that you sometimes see flying around. Just root, and keep nuking till they’re dead. If you do this solo you’ll need to go back to the Tunnel and med after each fight, which is why a tank partner is good.

You should hit 12 fast doing this, saving all the Lightstones and especially Greater Lightstones you get. Resist the temptation to sell these, even if they seem to be good money. You’ll get much better. You probably don’t have a lot of money right now, don’t worry, you soon will, but for now head back to Freeport and buy the spells Shock of Lightning and Bind Affinity. Those are the important ones.

Now, for the next stage of your life, you’ll want to head off to WC. You’ll still want to fight Wisps whenever you can, but as just about everything else in EC is now bad xp and never was that great for loot, WC is much better.

Set up shop at the Toll Booth, you’ll know it when you see it. If there are high levels there killing guards, you might want to make your base near the zone instead. Med to full, go after a Wisp, root, nuke, and loot. If there are no Wisps out, go after a Young Kodiak, but make sure there are no others around. Young Kodiaks rarely drop High Quality Bear Skins, which are worth 20pp or more, up to as much as 35 sometimes. So auction those off if you get them, and keep killing.

Many people will say, why aren’t you in Oasis fighting? Hah. Oasis is a very dangerous place, with 40+ mobs being trained all the time, and has nothing for loot whatsoever unless you’re fighting orcs. Meanwhile, you’re in WC getting great xp solo, while the downtime between fights isn’t all that long at level 12, and getting Lightstones and Greater Lightstones, which you’ll use to make more xp, and for GLS, much money.

If you’re not so solo inclined, in WC there is also a nice Dervish camp. A good group can handle the place, and you’ll still get very nice xp and pretty solid loot. So there’s a choice, it’s all a matter of how you want to play.

If you chose to fight Wisps, however, you’ll eventually have a lot of LS and GLS in your inventory. When you start to get full, head back over to EC, and go through the Tunnel to NRO. Now, you’ll have to go to Oasis, so be careful. When you get to NRO, turn SE until you hit the ocean, and just follow it south to the Oasis zone. Bind in the Tunnel on the EC side if you like to get back to action as soon as possible.

When you zone into Oasis, keep to the shore. You’ll eventually pass a dock, to your right there will be a sand hill. When you pass that turn right and run to the Gypsy camp. Give the LS to Synthan 4 at a time, but when you turn in GLS make sure you have open general inventory slots and don’t turn in more than you have open slots, because she gives you a container.

Now for the regular LS you won’t get much xp, but it’s still xp, and a small book you can sell back to her for 9sp or so. But for each GLS you get great xp and a container, like I mentioned, that you can then sell back to her for 9-10pp each. This is where you start making money.

When you’re finished here you can gate back. Depending on how many GLS you turned in you might have a lot of money and need to make a trip to FP Bank.

You could conceivably keep this up till 16 or so, but the xp dries up a lot by then. It would probably be better to do wisps until 14, or 15 if you can stand if for the money, and then go ahead to Oasis for a couple levels. By now you should have plenty of money for your 16 spells, so you don’t have to worry too much about loot.

Immediately try to get a group fighting either DW Caimans and Crocs or Orcs. The orcs drop decent loot, but can be a bit of trouble sometimes. Either way, the xp here is great at this level, and you’ll level fast.

When you hit 16, back to FP you go to buy your level 16 spells. You should be able to buy them all, but some are pretty useless, particularly Heat Sight, but also including Project Lightning, and, depending on how your groups pull, Pillar of Fire. I personally don’t like using AE spells, because while the tanks in the group are fighting one enemy, the other will tend to come after you.

You can stay here till level 20, but there’s a much better place to go at level 18. You’ll be amazed at the xp and loot. So, buy your level 20 Fay Gate spell and either get a port or hop a boat back to BB or Gfay and head back to the BB docks, but go over to the far left dock and sit down on one of the shuttles. Eventually they’ll take off with you and you’ll zone into Timorous Deep, where you’ll have to hop on a boat and ride to Kunark.

You’ll arrive in the fair city of Firiona Vie after a while, and you’ll want to definitely bind here. There are nasty things between here and the Lake of Ill Omen zone, which is where we’re headed next.

Stock up on food and water, 2 or 3 stacks of each is a good idea, and find your way to the bridge leading to the beach. Now you should probably try to get a sow, which is useful in making it to LOIO alive, but not absolutely necessary. Anyway, invis yourself and run along the beach until it meets a stream, then follow the stream. There will be Drachnids everywhere, who will roast you alive if you become visible again, but as long as you’re careful you’ll be ok. Just follow the stream and you’ll get to the LOIO zone.

Once there, shout for a Mill group. To get to the Mill, follow the stream until it dumps into the Lake, and turn left and follow the wall, you’ll be able to see it from a ways away. Some people like to bind here, it’s usually a good idea unless you like running through Drachnids again, which will rip you apart well into your 30s.

Once you get a group, you’ll be fighting goblins, sarnaks, sabretooths, and some skellies, all of which are great xp and loot. You’ll find yourself at level 20 in no time, at which point you’ll want to learn your Fay Gate spell so you can port yourself over to Gfay and buy the rest of your 20 spells. Now start thinking of a last name =)</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>&nbsp;</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>Strategy Submitted on: Wednesday, May 23, 2001</td></tr>
